  <bioghist id="6c5df0f0f0c933f3d7e2345a798f992d">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>The Ford Foundation launched the South Africa UPDATE Series project in the late 1980s in order to update the South Africa: Time Running Out report (SATRO). The Study Commission on U.S. Policy Towards Southern Africa published the SATRO report in 1981. The Commission was funded by the Rockefeller Foundation and chaired by Ford Foundation President Franklin Thomas.</p><p>
The UPDATE Series Editorial Board sought to update the SATRO report with a series of monographs that discussed recent political developments in South Africa. The Editorial Board emerged in part from the Ford Foundation's Southern Africa Study Group. Foundation staff members Franklin Thomas, Lynn Walker, and Gary Sick sat on the Board. John de St. Jorre served as Editor, Elinor Bowles served as Associate Editor, and Milfred Fierce served as Consulting Editor. </p><p>
Monographs in the series concern topics like international relations between South Africa and the United States, politics in the region of Southern Africa, political activism of black South Africans, reforms made to the Apartheid system, and the state of civil rights in South Africa.</p><p>
The five South Africa UPDATE monographs are titled:</p><p>
The United States and South Africa: The Reagan Years</p><p>
All, Here, and Now: Black Politics in South Africa in the 1980s</p><p>
Adapt or Die: The End of White Politics in South Africa</p><p>
Changing Fortunes: War, Diplomacy, and Economics in Southern Africa</p><p>
The Last Years of Apartheid: Civil Liberties in South Africa</p>  </bioghist>
  <processinfo id="2031121c691d7497ad2d3ad1220003b4">
    <head>Processing Information</head>
<p>Materials originated from a set of Ford Foundation program strategy records transferred to the RAC. Sequential box numbers on the original containers and analysis of the containers' contents suggested that the documents all related to the South Africa UPDATE Series. It was therefore decided to process the records as a discrete collection.</p><p>
Processing Level 3: Standard Processing</p><p>
Processed by Darren Young, September 2019</p>  </processinfo>
